Fishdata=read.csv("Fish.csv",header=TRUE)

1 Introduction

1.1 Build the best regression model you can that predicts the weight of perch

1.2 Using only two predictor variables

2 Methods

we are using numerical~numerical because the variables we are looking at are all explanatory variables.

#Results

2.1 Descriptive Results

2.1.1 Graphical Descriptive Results

FishiesP=filter(Fishdata, Species == "Perch")
FishiesP = select(FishiesP,-Species)
pairs(FishiesP)

FishiesB=filter(Fishdata, Species == "Bream")
FishiesB = select(FishiesB,-Species)
pairs(FishiesB)

FishiesS=filter(Fishdata, Species == "Smelt")
FishiesS = select(FishiesS,-Species)
pairs(FishiesS)

library(leaps)
regsubsets.out <-
    regsubsets(Weight ~ .,
               data = FishiesP,
               nbest = 1,       # 1 best model for each number of predictors
               nvmax = NULL,    # NULL for no limit on number of variables
               force.in = NULL, force.out = NULL,
               method = "exhaustive")

summary.out <- summary(regsubsets.out)
as.data.frame(summary.out$outmat)
##          Length1 Length2 Length3 Height Width
## 1  ( 1 )                              *      
## 2  ( 1 )                              *     *
## 3  ( 1 )                       *      *     *
## 4  ( 1 )               *       *      *     *
## 5  ( 1 )       *       *       *      *     *
